snippet.textDisplay:
Keeping with MCM tradition, our last episode of the year is out on Christmas Day. 

While Christmas is a day of celebration for a lot people, for many others it can be a difficult, lonely time particularly for those with broken families, severe financial stress, those dealing with the bush fire crisis or families dealing with the loss of a loved one. 

While we can’t fully understand what each person is going through, we want to acknowledge that for many people it won’t be the kind of Christmas we see on TV. 

Don’t worry about YouTube videos of people getting new super cars and houses or $1M for Christmas. This stuff is not reality and certainly not a basis to compare your own situation. The best gift you can give anyone is your attention - keep it simple and don’t give yourself a hard time if your Christmas Day doesn’t look like the ads on TV (nobodies Christmas Day actually looks like that) 

Huge respect to all of the emergency services personnel and volunteers that are battling bush fires around the country. And for those that need some extra help, please check out the ReachOut website where there is free support for those in need. 

All the best for the end of 2019 and we hope you enjoy the episode. 
- MCM

snippet.textDisplay: There seems to be a very easy way to reprogram the immobiliser on a Toyota. Use a paperclip or a piece of wire to bridge pin 4 and 13 on the OBD2 port. Then insert the key you want to use, in this case the Yaris key, and turn it to ON and leave it like that for 30 min. Then turn it off and remove the paperclip and you're good to go. It's a trick I found on Youtube so it must be true.

snippet.textDisplay: What a smart and clever swap.  Same engine family, near bolt-up...still plenty of fabrication and wiring.  Phenomenal bang for the buck.  Any idiot can throw cubic dollars at another over the top LS swap with a checkbook build, but it is nice to see a smart sleeper swap on an econo-box on the cheap.  Lightness is already there, so it doesn't need a lot more power to be a total hoot.  The hot hatch Toyota should have built.  This is a project any enthusiast can tackle with a little help.   THIS is what hot-rodding is all about.  Well done lads!

snippet.textDisplay: very interesting build.... apart from the fact you chucked the 6 speed but the fact that even the bell housing FITS as-is is really surprising... all toyotas from the 90s used essentially the same transmission (its a C series, even now) but the bell housing was not the same for the A and E series blocks, so you needed to do some surgery to get the transmissions to fit either one. We can NOW confirm the ZR and the NZ blocks have identical bell housing bolt holes... really very interesting what they did here.

snippet.textDisplay: 7:15 This question, the answer is why not? I have a tiny daily driver that weighs around 1900 pounds. It has a little 1.3L in it and does 0-60mph "eventually". The more I consider it, the more I want to swap the engine and transmission with maybe a Honda engine that can be turboed mated to a 5-speed. It might just fit, with some tweaks and maybe some fabrication. A car weighing less than 2K pounds with a hundred or two horsepower will fly. The car is already a rather nimble and well-handling car. I love how it handles. It takes corners very well at speed considering all the suspension components are still stock. The big things keeping me from "just doing it" is wondering if I can find any aftermarket performance parts to fit it without having to do too much fabrication. The car was never intended to be fast and the specific model I have had poor sales and was the last year the model was sold. It's already hard to find replacement parts. But that curb-weight and handling though, makes me want to try to get a couple hundred horses out of it.
